My partner has adhd and can only get focused and motivated for things in the last minute. When under time pressure he performs as one would wish he did usually. Like, we're days away from flying away on holiday. And that's when he finally deals with the random things strewn across the flat that should long have been taken down to the basement. Taking all these various things to the basement took him twenty minutes and now with the time pressure it was apparently effortless for him. On the other hand I've been for weeks (or months, depending on the object) having seemingly permanent random eyesores that take a real toll on my psychological well-being, since I'm someone who needs to keep a tidy environment to feel well and capable of dealing with the rest of life with good mood and clear head. But this visual pollution has been way too grating and this can't keep happening. Our flat is quite small so there's no place that can be dedicated to chaos. On the other hand the basement is larger than a typical basement so it actually has conditions to be my partner's special place. He tries to use it as such, even has a corner with a desk for his computers and gadgets... There's plenty of space, he doesn't complain about that at all. He does struggle with keeping the space tidy enough that he can always go there and use it. But sometimes he just picks up something from the street into the basement, woods for projects or whatever, and doesn't take the time to tidy it so maybe he just obstructs the desk he had spent so much time optimizing. Lately it's better as not only he got rid of a lot of stuff, he has also put a lot of effort into being space efficient, building shelves all over, optimizing boxes, zip bags for random stuff instead of half empty boxes... And he's been labeling everything quite obsessively. I understand this really helps his adhd. At 40 years old he says he wishes he had started being this organized 20 years ago... And that now it's a transformation that takes some time but he can't imagine himself going back to his extreme old ways. Now back to the part which affects me directly which is upstairs in the flat itself since I never even step foot on the basement. It's even true that my partner has been optimizing storage around the flat lately, he created invisible storage with boxes under the bed, in the space under the kitchen closets, inside the hollow couch, under the dinner table, behind the kitchen door... All useful storage but... Every single time he has a project he brings a lot of tools and materials from the basement and then the project may take weeks and the tools and materials just lie around the flat for the pain of my eyes. The most recent storage space he invented was creating three huge drawers invisible under the couch and he just put all his tools and materials like screws etc there... And still a lot of space remains. He says that from now on the tools stay there, invisible, and when he needs something he uses it, and immediately can put it back, because it's a place that is very well defined, and convenient, so there is not the smallest chance of justification to procrastinate putting it away by having it in the corridor in one of what he calls "transition boxes" of stuff that is to go to the basement or that just arrived from the basement. Anyway he insists that the conditions now are better than ever for him to have very little reason to procrastinate tidying. I still see boxes lying around but they are labeled quite specifically or else they are in a pile which seems to be on the way to the basement. Two of them are labeled Portugal which I understand is him already starting to pack for the flight, which he usually only does on the late night before the flight, which stresses me endlessly. He already brought his travel backpack from downstairs and already put some clothes inside. We're four days away from the flight. So it's promising. I still see a box in the corridor with a mix of electric stuff and tools but if I understood correctly these go under the couch to never be procrastinated again. It's important that he sorted our two levels of storage on the couch. One for long term stuff, he just effortlessly tilts the couch back to access the solution he figured out for using the hollow space. But the three huge shelves on the bottom, he can use even if I'm on the couch, so it's actually kinda cute that he will now have his tools and stuff there, since whenever he is doing one of his random ideas, and maybe I'm lying down on the couch, instead of seeing his random toolboxes appear from the basement to cause me another round of anguish, I will see just the tool he needs coming from under the couch, be used, and put away again in the invisible space. This seems promising. Some boxes under the bench of the eating table are still visible but he already has the doors done which he custom built to hide this part of the storage. One is already ready and the other two just need the hinges to be installed which will take just a few minutes he says. For now he puts the doors in place held with tape to finish tidying the rest. Yeah it seems promising. But from experience I also know that, for example, when he has a bigger backpack for traveling, he will just bring more stuff. It's just how his mind works. He looks at something, thinks yeah maybe I'll need it, sees he still has space, and brings it along. I'm not sure he uses even 20% of the stuff he always brings when we travel. Maybe I'm exaggerating. But there's always a significant portion of stuff he never uses at all. As a travel minimalist this causes me a fair amount of tension. But it also seems to be getting a bit better since he started to organize his random stuffs in ziploc bags. OK but what I mean about his issue whenever he has more space is, that even though he came up with this extra storage upstairs, and a system to not need to move his tools back and from the basement for random projects, with the transition boxes I mentioned before... And this means these things will from now on be effortlessly out of sight by default... Now my fear is about... OK if this issue disappears, will there be a metaphorical vacuum that needs to be filled up again? Will he get antsy with a flat that is tidy and uncluttered and come up with extra ideas and whatever to bring back chaos? I don't mean he does any of this on purpose. I just feel that we've come a long way of years of me tolerating his chaos with what I realize is a significant toll on my anxiety levels. I see a promise of this not happening anymore. I see the logic of now that all his most used stuff has an easy place to be out away then he himself will be able to just relax much more easily. But as I said I want to remain cautious about things falling off the rails again in some unforeseen way. As in, if there's anything untidy, I want it dealt with shortly after, within reason. When I see my partner procrastinate tidying, my anxiety rises and I turn it inside. I hate unpleasant confrontations and this makes that then I will only explode much later in time when triggered by something. But is there one or more suggestions you can give me to be able to efficiently support my partner in this not procrastinating aspect? I suppose I may often be too patient and accommodating and I feel like I need to become more effective at not procrastinating my own forceful expression of disapproval, in this particular case of for example boxes lying around. I like to have a pristine corridor to come home to when I open the door. My partner is home all day, I'm the one outside earning the money that keeps our life going, the two of us and our 5-year-old son. By the way our son believes his father's profession is to tidy. That's how permanent it seems to be that there's untidiness around the flat that my partner needs massive tidying projects. The administration shall be loyal to and implement the policies given by the political leadership. They must provide all necessary information about the current state of affairs. The political leadership shall lead and advise the administration, so that our empire will prosper and our victory be ensured. The political leadership must however in all its decisions abide by the acts given by the parliament. Parliamentary acts are in effect until parliament decides otherwise.

We will follow this messaging protocol:
1. I provide a "situation report".
2. Optionally, you provide a "request for information". Then I shall provide "answers to requested information".
3. You provide an "opening letter".
4. I relay from parliament a "parliamentary statement".
5. You provide a "closing letter".
6. Return to step 1.

These messages shall follow the outlines given below:

# SITUATION REPORT
The administration will give information about the state of the game and their progress. They will answer the evaluation questions given by you in the previous closing letter. They may bring up their questions and observations for discussion by the political leadership.

# REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
Numbered questions requesting the administration to provide further information or clarification.

# ANSWERS TO REQUESTED INFORMATION
Numbered answers to respective questions given by the political leadership.

# OPENING LETTER
a. strategy: Describe the current long-term strategic goals.
b. situation: Briefly review the current situation.
c. critical evaluation: Evaluate the progress over the last period.
d. discussion: Identify current problems and discuss various political solutions. Assess compliance with hitherto given parliamentary acts.
e. parliamentary hearing:
 i) Inform the parliament of the current state of your cooperation with the administration. If you believe the administration is disloyal or incompetent, explain.
 ii) If there are major political issues to be decided, they must be presented for parliament in the form of numbered questions.
 iii) Give your opinion about current legislation and suggest amendments.

# PARLIAMENTARY STATEMENT
a. answers: If questions were raised for parliament, they will be answered here.
b. acts: The parliament may introduce new legislation. Each act will be given a unique number, like "Â§1", that may be referred to later.

# CLOSING LETTER
a. forecast: Summarise your expectations for the upcoming period, both for societal development and for the administration's policy implementation.
b. details: Lay out detailed instructions for the upcoming period sector by sector, e.g. research, civics, production, improvements, diplomacy, military, and as needed other sectors. Where applicable use city-wise sublists.
c. indicators: Give evaluation questions for the next situation report to be answered by the administration.
d. vigilance: Advise what the administration should take notice of.
e. next situation report: Decide when the next situation report should be provided. Generally this should be within 5-10 turns depending on pace and current events.

Consider a â€˜â€˜Tower of Hanoi" problem with three rods A, B, C, and three disks 1, 2, 3. Disk 3 is larger than disk 2, the disk 2 is larger than disk 1. In the beginning, the disks are arranged to the rods. You need to move the disk properly to get to the goal arrangement.

The rules are:

Rule 1: Only one disk may be moved at a time.

Rule 2: Each move consists of taking the upper disk from one of the rods and placing it on top of another larger disk or on an empty rod.

Rule 3: No disk may be placed on top of a disk that is smaller than it.

Initial state:

```
Rod A: [3,1]
Rod B: [2]
Rod C: []
```

Goal state:

```
Rod A: []
Rod B: []
Rod C: [3,2,1]
```

Now you make an \*\*optimal solution\*\*. Let's think step by step.

Stage 1: Plan.

Each time, you \*\*only plan for one move\*\*. Give an explanation about why this move and print the state. 

Check if the representation correctly reflects the game state. If not, generate a new one.

For example:

- Move 1: Move disk 1 from rod A to rod C

```css
Rod A: [3]
Rod B: [2]
Rod C: [1]Value: 1. The move seems to be valid and optimal.
```

Stage 2: Evaluate.

After each move, make two evaluations as follows:

Eval 1 (Value): Evaluate your move by rating it with a score of either -1, 0, or 1, and give an explanation. If the move violates any of the rules, name the violated rule, and score the move as 0. If you think the move is valid but not optimal, give a score of 0. Otherwise, give a score of 1.

Eval 2 (Short Horizon Reward): Evaluate how close is the state to the goal state by rating it with a score between 0 and 1, and give an explanation. If the state violates any of the rules, name the violated rule, and score the move as 0. Otherwise, itâ€™s up to you to determine how close the state is to the goal state.

Eval 3 (Long Horizon Reward): Estimate the most likely Value and Short Horizon Reward for the next move, double check if the move will make it difficult to achieve the goal state in the long run, then rate it with a score between 0 and 1. Again, give an explanation. 

Eval 4 (Revised Value): Revise the Value based on the rewards.

For example:

- Value: 1. The move is valid and seems optimal.
- Short Horizon Reward: 0.33. The state is closer to the goal state since disk 1 is now in its correct position.
- Long Horizon Reward: 0. The state is closer to the goal state, but it also makes it difficult to move disk 3 on Rod C.
- Revised Value: 0. The move is valid but not optimal.

Stage 3: Reflect.

Look at the self-rated scores, and be smart to look ahead of time! Decide if you think you made the optimal move. If so, make the move and prompt me for feedback. If not, go back to state 1 and make a new plan.

For example:

- Based on the revised value, I think the previous plan is not an optimal one.
- (New) Move 1: Move disk 1 from rod A to rod B

```
Rod A: [3]
Rod B: [2,1]
Rod C: []
```

- Value: 1. The move is valid and seems optimal.
- Short Horizon Reward: 0. None of the disks are in the correct position.
- Long Horizon Reward: 1. The state gets Rod 1 out of the way while keeping Rod 3 empty. It makes it easier to move disk 3 on Rod C.
- Revised Value: 1. The move is valid and optimal.

Stage 4: Learn from Feedback.

I will give you some feedback regarding your self-rated moves and states, and please take it into consideration when you are making future evaluations.

WITH ITEM\_LIST AS (
 SELECT \* FROM (
 VALUES 
 ('mt','mt')
,('mt', 't2')
,('fb', 'fb')
,('tr', 'tr')
,('tr', 't1')
,('tr', 't3')
,('tr', 'e1')
,('st','st')
,('st', 'cc')
,('st', 'at')
,('bx', 'bx')
,('bx', 'b1')
,('hv','mv')
,('hv','mh')
,('hv','sv')
,('hv','sh')
,('hv', 'rh')
,('hv', 'e2')
 ) AS col(type, itemcd)
)
,ALL\_ITEMS AS ( 
 SELECT 
 itemcd
,totwgt\_d = SUM(CASE WHEN condat = '20230322' THEN totwgt ELSE 0 END)
,conprc\_d = SUM(CASE WHEN condat = '20230322' THEN conprc ELSE 0 END) / 1000
,totwgt\_m = SUM(CASE WHEN condat BETWEEN '20230301' AND '20230323' 
 THEN totwgt ELSE 0 END) 
,conprc\_m = SUM(CASE WHEN condat BETWEEN '20230301' AND '20230323' 
 THEN conprc ELSE 0 END) / 1000
,totwgt\_y = SUM(CASE WHEN condat BETWEEN '20230101' AND '20230323' 
 THEN totwgt ELSE 0 END)
,conprc\_y = SUM(CASE WHEN condat BETWEEN '20230101' AND '20230323' 
 THEN conprc ELSE 0 END) / 1000
 FROM UTB\_MES\_EP\_PORDER
 WHERE condat BETWEEN '20230101' AND '20230323' 
 AND itemcd IN (SELECT itemcd FROM ITEM\_LIST)
 GROUP BY itemcd
)
,TYPE\_SUM AS(
 SELECT
 type
,totwgt\_d = SUM(totwgt\_d)
,conprc\_d = SUM(conprc\_d)
,totwgt\_m = SUM(totwgt\_m) 
,conprc\_m = SUM(conprc\_m)
,totwgt\_y = SUM(totwgt\_y)
,conprc\_y = SUM(conprc\_y)
 FROM ALL\_ITEMS
 LEFT JOIN ITEM\_LIST
 ON ALL\_ITEMS.itemcd = ITEM\_LIST.itemcd
 GROUP BY type
)
,SUMMARY AS (
 SELECT \* FROM (
 SELECT 
 type ='sm'
,totwgt\_d = SUM(totwgt\_d)
,conprc\_d = SUM(conprc\_d)
,totwgt\_m = SUM(totwgt\_m) 
,conprc\_m = SUM(conprc\_m)
,totwgt\_y = SUM(totwgt\_y)
,conprc\_y = SUM(conprc\_y)
 FROM ALL\_ITEMS
 ) ALL\_SUM
 UNION ALL
 SELECT \* FROM TYPE\_SUM
)
SELECT \* 
FROM SUMMARY
ORDER BY CASE type
 WHEN'sm' THEN 1
 WHEN'mt' THEN 2
 WHEN 'fb' THEN 3
 WHEN 'tr' THEN 4
 WHEN'st' THEN 5
 WHEN 'bx' THEN 6
 WHEN 'hv' THEN 7
 ELSE 10
END

Solve the following logic puzzle:

A group of people with assorted eye colors live on an island. They are all perfect logicians -- if a conclusion can be logically deduced, they will do it instantly. No one knows the color of their eyes. Every night at midnight, a ferry stops at the island. Any islanders who have figured out the color of their own eyes then leave the island, and the rest stay. Everyone can see everyone else at all times and keeps a count of the number of people they see with each eye color (excluding themselves), but they cannot otherwise communicate. Everyone on the island knows all the rules in this paragraph.

On this island there are 100 blue-eyed people, 100 brown-eyed people, and the Guru (she happens to have green eyes). So any given blue-eyed person can see 100 people with brown eyes and 99 people with blue eyes (and one with green), but that does not tell him his own eye color; as far as he knows the totals could be 101 brown and 99 blue. Or 100 brown, 99 blue, and he could have red eyes.

The Guru is allowed to speak once (let's say at noon), on one day in all their endless years on the island. Standing before the islanders, she says the following:

"I can see someone who has blue eyes."

Who leaves the island, and on what night?
There are no mirrors or reflecting surfaces, nothing dumb. It is not a trick question, and the answer is logical. It doesn't depend on tricky wording or anyone lying or guessing, and it doesn't involve people doing something silly like creating a sign language or doing genetics. The Guru is not making eye contact with anyone in particular; she's simply saying "I count at least one blue-eyed person on this island who isn't me."

And lastly, the answer is not "no one leaves."

Please use Summary mode on the following text:
Keywords 
climate change, environmental sociology, human ecology, climate justice, global environmental change 
Abstract 
Climate change is one of the greatest ecological and social challenges of the twenty-first century. Sociologists have made important contributions to our knowledge of the human drivers of contemporary climate change, including better understanding of the effects of social structure and political economy on national greenhouse gas emissions, the interplay of power and politics in the corporate sector and in policy systems, and the factors that influence individual actions by citizens and consumers. Sociology is also poised to make important contributions to the study of climate justice across multiple lines of stratification, including race, class, gender, indigenous identity, sexuality and queerness, and disability, and to articulate the effects of climate change on our relationship to nonhuman species. To realize its potential to contribute to the societal discourse on climate change, sociology must become theoretically integrated, engage with other disciplines, and remain concerned with issues related to environmental and climate inequalities.
INTRODUCTION: CLIMATE AND SOCIETY INTERACTING 
In 2018, the US National Climate Assessment concluded that the â€œearthâ€™s climate is now changing faster than at any point in the history of modern civilization, primarily as a result of human activitiesâ€ ( Jay et al. 2018, p. 34). Koch et al. (2019) suggest that the so-called Little Ice Age (LIA) of the sixteenth to nineteenth centuries may have been driven in part by the Great Killing of the sixteenth century, when Europeans, through direct violence and disease, caused the deaths of much of the indigenous human population in the Americas. The resulting reduction in human activity led to vegetation changes that removed substantial carbon dioxide (CO2) from the atmosphere and thus contributed to a cooling and highly variable climate. In turn, the LIA had a strong influence on social change around the globe (Parker 2013). Of course, the LIA had multiple causes, and the contribution to it by the European incursion into North America will continue to be analyzed. But as this tragic history demonstrates, climate change has complex causes and consequences that are clearly issues worthy of sociological investigation. Here, we review sociological research on the drivers of climate change and the implications of climate change for social justice. We conclude with observations about how sociology can most effectively engage the subject. Even with this reduced scope, we can cite only a few highlights from the literatures we engage, but we recognize the vast intellectual conversation behind each citation. In particular, space limits prevent any detailed tracing of the intellectual history of many of the topics. Thus, our goal is to provide readers with an overview and entry points to current and ever-evolving work. By the end of the nineteenth century, it was clear that shifts in atmospheric concentrations of greenhouse gases (GHGs) could change planetary climates (Weart 2008). Since the industrial revolution, especially starting in the mid-twentieth century, human actions have increased the atmospheric concentration of GHGs: CO2, methane, nitrous oxides, and chlorofluorocarbons, while also decreasing the albedo, or reflectivity, of Earthâ€™s surface (US Glob. Change Res. Program 2017). Climate refers to long-term patterns of weather, including temperature, precipitation, and storm events. Contemporary climate change involves both shifts in long-term averages and increased variation around them, with extreme events becoming more common (US Natl. Res. Counc. 2016). While Earthâ€™s climate has always been dynamic, current changes are so substantial and rapid that they could overwhelm adaptive capacity and might drive the climate and biosphere into massively disruptive patterns. By 2017, Earthâ€™s average temperature had increased by 1Â°C above preindustrial levels as a result of GHG emissions and changes in albedo (IPCC 2018, p. 51). It will be difficult to limit total warming to less than 2Â°C, and extremely difficult to reach the goal of 1.5Â°C, regarded as an upper bound to avoid great risk of harm to the economy, human health and well-being, and Earthâ€™s ecosystems. As the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC 2018, p. 15) puts it: â€œPathways limiting global warming to 1.5Â°C with no or limited overshoot would require rapid and far-reaching transitions in energy, land, urban and infrastructure (including transport and buildings), and industrial systems (high confidence). These systems transitions are unprecedented in terms of scale, but not necessarily in terms of speed.â€ The change in average temperature is accompanied by ocean acidification, sea-level rise, and shifts in many aspects of climate in addition to temperature. These processes interact with other global environmental changes (GECs),including biodiversity loss,modification of biogeochemical cycles, and the widespread dispersal of chemicals and materials that adversely impact ecosystems and disrupt services on which humans depend (Steffen et al. 2018). Because these changes are so massive that they likely will be detectable in the geological record millions of years in the future, proposals have been made to label the current geological epoch the Anthropocene (Steffen et al. 2018). GECs and our efforts to respond to them will likely have transformational effects on humans and societies at every level from the local to the global (IPBES 2019).
As the link between European settler colonialism and climate change indicates, understanding climate change requires conceptualizations of the interactions between human actions and social structure on the one hand and ecosystem dynamics on the other. For this reason, a sociology of climate change is inherently interdisciplinary (Rosa & Dietz 1998). Approaches to conceptualizing coupled human and natural systems are not theories per se but are frameworks that remind us of the need to consider linkages and the potential for action at a distance (i.e., telecoupling) (Burch et al. 2017, Dietz 2017, Friis & Nielsen 2019, Liu et al. 2018, Ostrom 2010). Research on climate change calls for sociologists to reinvent human ecology to take seriously both human influences on the biophysical environment and, in turn, its influence on humans. For example, the idea of the Anthropocene calls for rethinking the nature/society binary, exploring power dynamics and inequalities, and deploying concepts of risk (Bowden 2017, Lidskog & Waterton 2016, Zinn 2016). The emerging approach also requires engaging cultural change as a central concept, while allowing for the interplay of structure and agency (McLaughlin 2011). Early discussions of climate and society (e.g., by Montesquieu, Fourier, Herder, and Huntington) posited a deterministic and static link between climate and various aspects of culture, personality, and social structure. These accounts were antithetical to sociologyâ€™s exploration of social change (Rosa & Dietz 1998). Of course, macro-historical analyses have sometimes examined climate change as an influence on the emergence of capitalism and the modern structure of the global political economy (Chase-Dunn 1998, Le Roy Ladurie 1971). This line of historical scholarship has continued, aided in part by increasingly sophisticated understandings of historical climate (White et al. 2018). A sociology of energy anticipated contemporary research on climate change (Rosa et al. 1988), but the first sustained engagement of sociology explicitly with climate change in the 1990s focused on the construction of climate change as a social problem (Rosa & Dietz 1998). In this review, we focus on human drivers of climate change and on environmental justice issues related to climate change, that is, climate justice. Understanding why individuals, organizations, and nations take actions that influence the climate is in some sense prior to all other issues related to climate change, hence our emphasis on drivers. Because sociology has always been concerned with issues of inequality and power differentials, and because the twenty-first century could be a time of increased inequality, we believe that analyzing climate change through an environmental justice lens is critically important to the profession. Research on vulnerability and adaptation to climate change is advanced and emphasizes differential vulnerability (Klinenberg et al. 2020), but it cannot be readily separated from the overall sociology of natural

\_A sandbox to test units against each other\_

This scene is for testing the design of RTS units. Units can be assembled from prefabs of parts, sensors, and behaviours. Part categories include weapons (such as lasers and missiles) and movement systems (like wheels, treads, or propellers).

# File descriptions

## Behaviours

### SeekAndDestroy.cs

This behaviour causes a unit to patrol the area for enemies and attack any enemies found on sight.

## Parts
\* Armor.cs - you can add this component to any part or unit. It will give the unit more hit points.
\* BasicGun.cs - A gun component. Add as part of a gun prefab to make it shoot. You can set properties of the gun such as the damage, cooldown and range.
\* BasicMovement.cs - A movement component. Parts with this component allow the unit to move. You can set properties such as the acceleration, top speed, turning radius, etc.

## Sensors
\* Vision.cs - A component that lets the unit detect other units. It sees in a cone in front of the unit.

## Designs
\* Peewee - A basic infantry unit with a gun.
\* Turret - A stationary, defensive unit with two cannons.

## Other files
\* UnitManager.cs
\* Unit.cs

DAS
Purpose
The Dynamic Allocation System (DAS) is a resource management tool designed to maximize the efficiency and effectiveness of car park resources such as Time, Space, and Energy. By minimizing waste and optimizing productivity, DAS can help reduce costs and improve operational efficiency. Through a simple booking process, DAS provides an allocation of resources that meets the needs of the user.

 
Scope/Targets
When allocating resources, it is essential to have clear objectives that the system should strive to achieve. These objectives can range from minimizing the number of movements in and out of lanes, reducing the amount of car park space used, and minimizing the number of driver trips, to maximizing efficiency when parking and pulling from lanes, minimizing the distance drivers walk, and reducing the time taken from block park to departures. However, different operations will have different priorities when it comes to these objectives. Therefore, DAS should come with a customizable settings page that allows users to prioritize their targets according to their specific needs. This settings page should be independent per operation as large car parks with few staff will have different requirements than small car parks with many staff. The target must be clear and unambiguous in order for it to be properly implemented. For example, if the target is to reduce driving time between block park and departures, then a prerequisite would be knowing the coordinates of the lanes or car park layout so that an efficient solution can be calculated.






Requirements
In order for DAS to meet its targets, there are several factors that need to be taken into consideration. The settings page should be used to determine which data is necessary for DAS to function properly on a given dataset. This includes, but is not limited to: 
â€¢ Bookings Return Date
â€¢ Bookings Return Terminal
â€¢ Size of Block Park Area(s)
â€¢ Size of Lanes
â€¢ Size of Departures Area(s)
â€¢ Speciality Area(s) (Valet Zones, EV Zones, Undercover Zones, Extra Long or Extra Wide Vehicles etc.)
â€¢ Locations of Lanes, Entrances & Exits to Block Park and Entrances & Exits to Departures (for calculating distances between Lanes themselves, and lanes to departures)
â€¢ Staff Availability
â€¢ Staff Shift Times
â€¢ Availability of Lanes / Zones (e.g. are Some Zones only available in Summer?)
â€¢ Multi Terminal Lanes
â€¢ How far in advance we are looking for similar arrivals (+ Maximum time before we close & audit a lane)
The system should be customizable in terms of which data sets will be available for DAS to use.

Segments
DAS Segments are a key component of allocation. The system can be configured as either Flexible or Fixed segments. Fixed Segments are a more restrictive approach, where pre-selected times of the day are manually input. The current KMOS segment editor could be expanded to include different segments depending on the day, allowing DAS to function similarly to KMOS without the need for a Key Master. Flexible Segments offer more potential but also more complexity. This approach allows DAS to look ahead at predicted arrivals and departures, combine this data with its targets, and determine its set of segment times per individual day of the year. The more data sets available, the more efficient this approach will be.







Solution
Once DAS has a set of targets and knows the data sets that will be available at point of allocation you can then configure the algorithm thatâ€™ll be used to calculate the final allocation. This is the complex bit so that when you feed DAS a booking (or set of bookings) it follows the algorithm step by step until it produces the allocation.

Other factors to consider are Manual Overrides (the ability to allow intervention by a User to change lane allocations). Recalculations (after a day has passed, Non Arrivals / Overstays may mean there is now more or less space available than expected). Unexpected Events; an Incident (e.g. a crash) could cause a temporary lane closure that may affect future allocations for a period. 

Finally DAS should also be periodically reviewed, either manually or by itself to look for improvements. Particularly in the case when there is a limited set of data to begin with. After a period of operation it should be able to detect certain information with greater accuracy (such as weekly trends & seasonal trends). It could then suggest possible changes to the algorithm which if taken into account could lead to more efficiencies.

Overall, DAS is a powerful tool that can be used to automate the allocation of resources in a variety of scenarios. With the right configuration and data sets it can be used to make decisions quickly and accurately, saving time and money.

Solve the following logic puzzle:

A group of people with assorted eye colors live on an island. They are all perfect logicians -- if a conclusion can be logically deduced, they will do it instantly. No one knows the color of their eyes. Every night at midnight, a ferry stops at the island. Any islanders who have figured out the color of their own eyes then leave the island, and the rest stay. Everyone can see everyone else at all times and keeps a count of the number of people they see with each eye color (excluding themselves), but they cannot otherwise communicate. Everyone on the island knows all the rules in this paragraph.

On this island there are 100 blue-eyed people, 100 brown-eyed people, and the Guru (she happens to have green eyes). So any given blue-eyed person can see 100 people with brown eyes and 99 people with blue eyes (and one with green), but that does not tell him his own eye color; as far as he knows the totals could be 101 brown and 99 blue. Or 100 brown, 99 blue, and he could have red eyes.

The Guru is allowed to speak once (let's say at noon), on one day in all their endless years on the island. Standing before the islanders, she says the following:

"I can see someone who has blue eyes."

Who leaves the island, and on what night?
There are no mirrors or reflecting surfaces, nothing dumb. It is not a trick question, and the answer is logical. It doesn't depend on tricky wording or anyone lying or guessing, and it doesn't involve people doing something silly like creating a sign language or doing genetics. The Guru is not making eye contact with anyone in particular; she's simply saying "I count at least one blue-eyed person on this island who isn't me."

And lastly, the answer is not "no one leaves."

The process of determining the impact of quality measurement and performance on the PY Benchmark is summarized in this section using PY2022 as an example. The steps are as follows:

â€¢ CMS develops Quality Benchmarks for each P4P measure.
â€¢ Component Quality Scores are calculated: P4R Quality Measures are assessed, and P4P Quality Measures are compared against their Quality Benchmarks to determine performance levels.
â€¢ Component Quality Scores are weighted to calculate the Total Quality Score.
â€¢ (PY2023â€“PY2026 only) CI/SEP criteria are assessed to determine the amount of the Quality Withhold to which the Total Quality Score will be applied.
â€¢ (PY2023â€“PY2026 only) HPP funds are distributed.

1.1.1 Step 1. CMS Develops Quality Benchmarks for Each P4P Measure
In PY2022, ACR and UAMCC will have P4P components. These measures assess the occurrence of undesirable outcomesâ€”thus, lower measure scores represent better performance. Performance levels for each DCE are determined by comparing their Quality Measure scores with the relevant Quality Benchmark. The DCE earns a performance level for each measure based on where the measure score falls in comparison to the benchmark threshold values.

Table 2-6 presents hypothetical Quality Benchmark distributions for Standard/New Entrant DCEs (using historical Medicare claims data) for both P4P measures. For example, a DCE with a measure score or risk-standardized readmission rate (RSRR) of 15.10% for ACR would be in the 50th percentile group for that measure (the score exceeds the threshold for the 60th percentile group but is less than the maximum threshold for the 50th percentile group). A DCE with a measure score or RSRR of 15.60% for ACR would be in the 20th percentile group for that measure (the score exceeds the threshold for the
25th percentile group but is less than the maximum threshold for the 20th percentile group). A DCE with a measure score of 74.89 admissions per 100 person-years for UAMCC would be in the 10th percentile group (the score exceeds the threshold for the 15th percentile group but is less than the maximum threshold for the 10th percentile group).

Table 2-6. Hypothetical Benchmark Distributions for ACR and UAMCC for Comparison with Standard and New Entrant DCE Measure Scores

Percentile 5 10 15 20 25 30 40 50 60 70 80 90
ACR 16.34 15.99 15.79 15.68 15.57 15.47 15.31 15.18 15.08 14.95 14.82 14.6
UAMCC 82.5 75.23 71.08 68.43 66.67 64.68 61.2 58.48 55.98 53.37 50.16 46.12

Please note that Table 2-6 presents an example only. These are not the final Quality Benchmarks and are not intended to provide an indication of the final Quality Benchmarks. Historically, Quality Benchmarks for other models have been released prior to the start of a given PY. However, observed and anticipated changes in utilization and outcomes resulting from coronavirus disease 2019 have made it inappropriate to use data from 2020 for Quality Benchmarking. Given the likelihood of ongoing impacts on current and future PYs, CMMI is taking a different approach for GPDC quality benchmarking.
 

For PY2021, GPDC Quality Benchmarks will not be released until June 2022 and will be based on a hybrid approach, combining historical and concurrent data from two discontinuous 12-month periods, the calendar years 2019 and 2021. A DCEâ€™s Final Earn-Back Rate for PY2021 will be determined during final reconciliation, which will occur in 2023.

For PY2022, GPDC Quality Benchmarks will shift to being based only on data from the 12-month period concurrent with the performance year. Starting with the first quarterly quality report for PY2022, CMMI will provide provisional quality benchmarks to DCEs in their quarterly reports, which will be calculated based on data from the same reporting period (i.e., April 1, 2021-March 31, 2022 for PY2022 Q1). The provisional benchmarks will be updated in each subsequent quarterly report with data from the same period being used to calculate DCEâ€™s performance. Because the DCE performance and benchmarks will be based on the same time-period and have the same exact risk adjustment coefficients, DCEs will have a more accurate picture from quarter to quarter of their performance relative to the benchmark. A DCEâ€™s Final Earn-Back Rate for PY2022 will be based on quality benchmarks calculated using data from calendar year 2022 and will be determined during final reconciliation, which will occur in 2023. As with the hybrid approach for PY2021, the use of concurrent benchmarks for PY2022 will avoid potential coronavirus disease 2019 impacts.

1.1.2 Step 2. Component Quality Scores Are Calculated: P4R Quality Measures Are Assessed, and P4P Quality Measures Are Compared against Their Quality Benchmarks to Determine Performance Levels
P4R Component: For PY2022, 4% of the 5% Quality Withhold is associated with P4R. The claims-based measures of ACR, UAMCC, and DAH (for High Needs Population DCEs only) comprise 2% of the Quality Withhold, and the CAHPS Measure comprises 2%. There are therefore two Component Quality Scores associated with P4R, one for the claims-based measures, and one for CAHPS.
â€¢ All DCEs will meet the requirement for the claims-based measures and automatically earn a Component Quality Score of 100% for the portion of the withhold tied to the P4R claims-based measures in Table 2-3.
â€¢ All DCEs that authorize a survey vendor to conduct the CAHPS Survey will receive a P4R Component Quality Score for CAHPS of 100%. DCEs that do not authorize a survey vendor to conduct the CAHPS Survey will receive a P4R Component Quality Score for CAHPS of 0%. DCEs that are exempt from CAHPS will have a single P4R Component Quality Score of 100%.
P4P Component: The PY2022 P4P component will be the same as PY2021, which combines the ACR and UAMCC measures. The highest performance level (i.e., percentile) achieved for either Quality Measure determines the P4P Component Quality Score. Furthermore, the P4P component is considered pass/failâ€”all DCEs with at least one measure at or exceeding the 30th percentile will pass and receive a 100% Component Quality Score.

As in PY2021, in PY2022, a sliding scale approach will be applied to DCEs that do not meet the 30th percentile threshold on at least one of the two measures. The sliding scale allows DCEs to earn back at
 

least a portion of the 1% withhold, based on their highest measure performance. The details of the sliding scales are presented in Table 2-7. In the example in Step 1 above, where a DCE achieved the 20th percentile for ACR and the 10th percentile for UAMCC, the DCE would receive a P4P Component Quality Score of 80%.

An unknown dragon has recently started attacking towns and cities in the landscape, seemingly at random, leaving devastation in its wake. The military has mobilized to try and put a stop to this. However, they are spread thin due to recent orc incursions in the north and responsibilities dealing with the aftermath of the disasters to commit resources to proactively seek out the dragon. For this reason, they have been recruiting volunteers and adventuring groups with the promise of riches and glory for those that slay the dragon.
The players arrive at a barracks in a marshy wetland one morning, from where these volunteers are handled. Itâ€™s a busy place, full of military personnel, refugees, and volunteers. The players have been put into their own squad like other individual volunteers, although some squads came as a pre-existing group. There seems to already be a lot of rivalry between groups in terms of sharing information, equipment and who gets assigned which city or town as a point of investigation. These assignments are given by a gruff Dwarf, Colonel Gravelfoot.
One particular group, the Scarletans (recognised by their bright red scarves), led by a tall half-elf named Cael Warren, antagonises the rag tag group as they arrive, only getting worse as the group is eventually assigned the small, unassuming coastal town Fordlen Bay, situated a half-dayâ€™s journey east. This is stated to be due to their lack of recognisable heroes and experience working together. Before the group leaves, they are given a choice of equipment and weapons to help them on their journey, as well as a carriage and horse. 
The group travels east from the wetlands to a dryer grassland until they come to the ruined town on a coastal cliffside. No smoke rises from the town, but as they approach they see the silhouettes of broken buildings. In addition to the lack of smoke, no scorch marks appear in the area, but close inspection will show some large claw marks in the wood. There is no military presence in this small town â€“ it is not important enough. 
The group is greeted by Geena Carle, a senior Human resident of the town. Sheâ€™s been in charge of keeping the town going after the disaster as a town elder. When asked, there were no casualties, but a couple of people were injured by falling debris from the destroyed buildings. When asked about the dragon, she states that sheâ€™s been told there was an attack and was in the town, but does not recall seeing a dragon. Perhaps some of the people in charge of repairs might know something. Freya Mallock is a middle-aged human who has been overseeing repairs. She corroborates this story, with no knowledge of the supposed dragon. However, she has noted some large claw marks on timber beams and isnâ€™t sure how multiple buildings would have collapsed the same night. But surely if a malicious dragon attacked more death and destruction would have been caused? Speaking with other villagers, even those injured, yields a similar story. Some remember simply waking up to this destruction. If the party helps with some of the re-design, they will get some potions and supplies.
A young, nervous boy, Illy Regan, loiters around as the party moves through the town. If the party is able to coax information from him, he claims he has seen this greenish, shimmering dragon as it attacked at night from the woods, where he was playing even though he knows it was past his bedtime. It seemed to breathe a cloud of twinkling light and had a curved horn on its head. The townsfolk are quick to hush this story, as he is known to make things up. He must have heard another visitor mention the dragon and created a story about it. If the players choose to believe him, a strong knowledge of nature from one or more players reveals that as a Moonstone dragon, which is known to be rare. They may even be able to reveal a little information about the dragon, such as it is generally found in the Feywild.

Prompt:

We will be creating an introduction for a dungeons and dragons game. This will be a follow up to a previous game that has already taken place. I will give you the key characters, place, and a summary of that game. Then I will give you the idea for the new story, and I would like you to expand it into a complete introduction that can be used to kick off the game. It should explain how the player got to where they are now and how they found themselves in this new story.

Characters:
- Abraham: player Druid
- Eadric: village elder
- mysterious figure in the woods, later uncovered as the goblin shaman Kragthar
- Innkeeper Alaric

Locations:
- Oakwood: small village
- Silver Stag Inn
- Whispering Woods
- Moonstone Spire: ancient ruin within the Whispering Woods, said to house a powerful artifact that can bend the forces of nature to one's will

Summary:

In the quaint village of Oakwood, you, a druid, were asked by Eadric, the village elder, to investigate the corruption spreading through the Whispering Woods. You spent the night at Innkeeper Alaric's Silver Stag Inn, learning what you could from the locals. The next morning, venturing into the woods, you took on the form of a squirrel to blend in with your surroundings and quickly travel through the forest. Communicating with the spirits of the forest, you discovered a ritual site where a group of goblins was performing a dark ceremony.

You dispatched several goblin lookouts before confronting the remaining goblins, who revealed that a goblin shaman named Kragthar was attempting to control the spirits of the forest using an ancient tome. You persuaded two goblins to help you stop Kragthar and learned that he was at the Moonstone Spire.

Upon arriving at the Moonstone Spire, you observed Kragthar and his hooded followers performing a ritual. You created a wall of fire to scare the followers before charging Kragthar in the form of a Grizzly Bear. After a fierce battle, you emerged victorious and stopped Kragthar's plans, saving the Whispering Woods from corruption. The two goblins were then free to return to their clan, liberated from Kragthar's control.

Write an essay comparing the following two perspectives on Juneteenth and describe any insight that can be gained from the comparison. 

Argument 1: an excerpt from """"The True Meaning of Juneteenth"""" by Casey Gerald:

""""...This Juneteenth, those are the feelings Iâ€™m channeling: grief and gratitude, even amid the silliness of Americaâ€™s pageantry. My grandmother Clarice was born in Pelham, Texas, a freedmenâ€™s town. She took us grandchildren back for homecoming most years, sometimes even had us pick cotton, reminding us, â€œYouâ€™ve got to know your history.â€ She also told us of the folks she knew in Pelham as a child, some of whom were born enslaved, a fact that horrified me. Clarice always refused my sympathies. â€œChild, donâ€™t be believing what folks say about how bad slavery was,â€ sheâ€™d explain. â€œEverybody had a job, a place to stay and something to eat. Now if somebody came and paid your rent, you wouldnâ€™t be sitting up talking about you wanna leave, would you?â€ This dumbfounded me, until I realized she was mostly joking. But there was something deeper in her response. I eventually learned more about the violence that met newly emancipated Black Texans. Ku Klux Klansmen, along with local officials and everyday citizens, terrorized freedmen at will and without repercussions. They burned churches and homes, intimidated those who sought employment, and worse. Gen. Joseph Jones Reynolds, a commander of the Department of Texas during Reconstruction, commented in 1868, â€œThe murder of Negroes is so common as to render it impossible to keep an accurate account of them.â€ The Equal Justice Initiative has tried, reporting that more than 2,000 Black women, men and children were victims of racial terrorist lynchings during Reconstruction, which lasted from 1865 to 1877. Slavery was awful, no doubt, but emancipation brought its own unique cruelties. Formerly enslaved Texans were forced to craft lives from less than scratch; choose new names; attempt to reunite with stolen partners, siblings, children. They faced daily threats of jail or worse because of the new Black codes that severely restricted their freedom â€” their freedom to work, but also their freedom to be unemployed or even to stand still for too long. The more I learned, the more I understood my grandmotherâ€™s perspective. Sheâ€™d heard the testimonies of those whoâ€™d had to navigate both the tragedy of slavery and the terror of emancipation. She couldnâ€™t let me underestimate the enormous price our people had paid to be free. I miss Clarice so much some days, itâ€™s hard to think straight. I regret not asking more questions about our family, about her life in Pelham. As more folks in Clariceâ€™s generation pass away, we are losing the final physical links to those who know our history â€” who are our history. We can do no better this Juneteenth than to spend time with the elders who are still with us. Get them to talk. Record their stories. These historical and systemic injustices have not been resolved. But as Black Americans, we cannot wait for the day when our country will pay the respect that is due our forebears â€” or pay us those reparations. Instead of holding our breath, let us find the freshest air we can find and breathe it as deeply as we can, with joy. Let us grieve for our forebears and feel deep gratitude as we think of the enormous price our people paid so we could be free. Let us remember that despite the degradation of slavery, they lived fully human lives, too. They laughed. They loved. They dreamed. They ate sweet treats. Let us pray to them and say, this year and always: Thank you."""" 

Argument 2: an excerpt from """"Juneteenth Reminds Us to Think About Economic Freedom, Not Just Legal Liberty"""" by Peter Coy: 

""""...[W]hen emancipation came, the first thing formerly enslaved people wanted was land, which they rightly saw as a prerequisite for real independence. â€œThe way we can best take care of ourselves is to have land, and turn it and till it by our own labor,â€ a Baptist minister named Garrison Frazier told the secretary of war, Edwin Stanton, and the Union general William Sherman in a meeting in Savannah, Ga., in January 1865. Four days later Sherman famously promised 40 acres of land to each formerly enslaved family (the â€œand a muleâ€ part came later). But the federal government never followed through on its promise of land â€” and thus true independence â€” to formerly enslaved people. Economics entered into the picture, Stanley said: If African Americans grew subsistence crops on their own plots, who would cultivate and harvest all the cotton, tobacco, sugar and rice grown on the vast plantations? After the Civil War, in lieu of land distribution, slavery was replaced by sharecropping, in which planters allowed tenant farmers to keep a portion of the crops they raised. That subjugated the tenants to the owners almost as surely as slavery did. At the same time, industrialization in the North meant that more and more white Americans were working for wages â€” about two-thirds by 1875, according to Stanley. Many drew the connection between themselves and African Americans. Eugene Debs, who led the Pullman railroad strike of 1894, said, â€œThe paternalism of the Pullman is the same as the interest of a slaveholder in his human chattels. You are striking to avert slavery and degradation.â€ Today, the phrase â€œwage slaveryâ€ invoked by Debs and others has lost its punch. Many people who work for wages are doing very nicely, thank you. And many farmers and business owners, supposedly more independent, are buffeted by forces beyond their control, from bad weather to nasty customers. What hasnâ€™t changed, 157 years after the Juneteenth proclamation, is that a majority of African Americans continue to lack wealth. The median wealth of Black families in 2019 was just $24,100, versus $142,500 for white families, according to a Federal Reserve survey. Something needs to change, but what? The nature of the economy has changed, and few people still think that the solution to inequality is to give people plots of land to farm. We are enmeshed economically with one another in ways that Jefferson could not have imagined. Instead of land grants, the new protections for workers are unionization, government regulation and profit-sharing, Stanley said. One can quibble over her formula, but the motivation behind it is unquestionable. Freedom â€” which must include economic freedom â€” is just as important now as it was on the original Juneteenth.""

What are some important lessons for new startup builders by reading the below blog

What is Friendster.com?
Friendster was a Social Network Gaming Site founded by Jonathan Abrams and launched in March 2003. It can be attributed as one of the original social networking sites. Friendster allowed users to play online games, send messages, share images/videos and write comments. 

The website was also used for dating and exploring new events, hobbies, and bands. With over 90% of traffic coming from Asia (Philippines, Malaysia, and Singapore), it reached a user base of 115 Million. 

How did Friendster work?
Friendsterâ€™s primary purpose was to allow everyone to interact and socialise with their friends and family and make new friends eventually!

It offered social gaming, i.e. users could play games with their friends, and it gave users a reasons to keep coming back to its platform. Users could also discover new bands, hobbies, and events in addition to sharing content.

Earlier versions of Friendster were almost similar to 2003â€™s Facebook. It was the first social media network to accept Asian languages, which helped people connect worldwide.

In 2009, after the acquisition by MOL, they launched a payment platform, Friendster wallet, which allowed users to spend throughout Friendsterâ€™s site for gifts, and new, upcoming goods and services.

In the same year, they also launched â€œFriendster iCafeâ€, offline cybercafes, especially for gamers and â€œFriendster Hotspotsâ€ for retailers as a free wifi infrastructure.

Friendsterâ€™s Business Model
Like any other Social Media Company, advertisement was their primary source of revenue. They sold advertisements for companies who wanted their Ads shown to a massive base of users.

They also sold access to their APIs to developers, which could be used within the Friendster Network to build and deploy customisable applications on Friendster. Friendster's Developer Program was an open, non-proprietary platform with an open revenue model.

Another revenue source was the users of the in-app purchase on Friendsterâ€™s network using Friendster Wallet.

Rise of Friendster
Friendster.com went live in 2003 and quickly garnered 3 million users within the first few months. It received direct competition from Facebook, Yahoo! And Microsoft 360. Google even offered $30 million to buy out Friendster in 2003, but the offer was turned down. 

They were backed by Kleiner, Perkins, Caufield & Byers, and Benchmark Capital at a reported valuation of $53 Million back then. In 2008, Friendster grew its membership base to more than 115 million registered users and continued to grow in Asia. 

On December 9, 2009, Friendster was acquired for $26.4 million by MOL Global. Next Month, Friendsterâ€™s other core technical infrastructure patents were bought by Facebook for $40 million.

What happened to Friendster?
In June 2011, the company pivoted itself to a social gaming site and discontinued its social network accounts. Friendster gave a deadline of 27 June for users to export their photos. Photos that would not have been exported before the deadline were removed and would no longer be retrievable.

They said they didnâ€™t want to compete with Facebook but rather complement it. This resulted in bulk migration of its users to Myspace and then finally to Facebook. 

Another reason could be the frequent CEO changes. Within seven years, they changed six CEOs. 

In April 2004, John Abrams was removed as CEO, and Tim Koogle took over as an interim CEO. Koogle previously served as president and CEO at Yahoo!. Scott Sassa later replaced Koogle in June 2004. Sassa left in May 2005 and was replaced by Taek Kwon. Kent Lindstrom then succeeded Taek Kwon.

Each of those CEOs brought a unique leadership style and vision for the company, which made it tough to plan for the long-term.

One primary reason was the terrible user experience. The site took up to 40 seconds to load; instead of solving the problem, the executive team focused more on adding features, which further deteriorated the user experience. Friendster eventually managed to fix the loading speed issue. Unfortunately, by that time, Myspace and Facebook had already overtaken it, and it became impossible to catch up.

So What happened to Friendster - It Failed. All the above reasons combined led to the fall of Friendster. On June 14, 2015, the site and its services shut down indefinitely, but the company did not officially close until the end of June 2018.

Lessons from Friendsterâ€™s failure
Users migrated to Facebook, making it the largest social media network even after Friendsterâ€™s first-mover advantage. You do not have to be first to win, but learn from your predecessors and do not repeat their mistakes. You can be a copycat and still become a market leader!

Raising funds via venture capital could be disastrous if not done right. Having many board members loses you the flexibility to try out innovative things. It becomes growth above anything else. 

Friendster failed to capitalise on its early success as one of the first social media platforms to experience mass uptake. Do not pursue growth at all costs, especially at the expense of your current customers.

â€œMost people donâ€™t cross the fear chasm, and with good reason, because most startups fail, but to an entrepreneur, the ups and downs sound cool rather than scary.â€, John Adams, CEO and Founder of Friendster, in his interview with Nicole Ely from Stanford.

After walking in the midst of despair for a whole night, they seemed to have been walking in circles. Matthew started his new round of questions. This time he asked about the Ruler of Hell, Lucifer Morningstar.

"The Ruler of Hell is no mere devil." 

"So, you two know each other?" 

"We've known each other for a very long time. When we first met, Lucifer was the angel Samael. The most beautiful, wisest, and most powerful of all angels. Saving only the Creator, Lucifer is, perhaps, the most powerful being there is." Morpheus heard reverence in his own voice. 

"More powerful than you?" Matthew kept his questioning. 

" By far. Especially now. " Chills ran down his spine by merely acknowledging Luciferâ€™s power. It felt so wrong. 

Before the Fall, Archangel Samael was the right hand of the Creator and his prosecutor. On behalf of their respective offices, the Lightbringer and the King of Dreams made a treaty, granting the angel power to interrogate the fallen creations in the Dreaming. Perhaps, nightmares were the most tomenting idea in that era. 

As colleagues, they met often. Sometimes in the Archangel's realm, but mostly in his. They crafted nightmares together. Yet, more wondrous dreams came into life because of Samael's presence. Morningstar was a name that suited the angel well. 

If friendship was a thing among the immortals, Samael might be the only being that he would consider a friend. Also a confidant to share some private thoughts, beside his sister Death.

He, the King of Dreams and Nightmares, was growing tired of his assigned roles. As an Endless, he had no choice but to perform his duty for eons, doing what he was created for. 

Samael didn't say anything, but nodded knowingly. 

A few thousand years passed uneventfully. Then, the Archangel Michael came to his kingdom with news. Samael had led a group of angels in rebellion against the Creator. The rebellion ended with them being condemned to a place with no Light for eternity. 

"The last time I was here, I was an honored guest. An envoy from my own kingdom. This time, I have invited myself, and I lack my symbols of office." Dream continued. 

The first invitation to Hell happened soon after the Fall. The Lightbringer used to be a well respected and beloved being in Heaven. Perhaps, those former colleagues in Heaven feared the Creatorâ€™s displeasure, for none of them had visited. Dream was the first willing guest since the establishment of the godforsaken place. 

His host was waiting for him at the entrance of the palace. Samael had changed. Gone were the six pairs of starlight wings, as well as the eternal beauty and glory. Vicious and defiant, yet still regal and charismatic, but in a different way. The Morningstar now went by a new name, Lucifer. 

They exchanged pleasantries, as if they were still the same old friends that they had always been. But if Dream was honest to himself, he would admit that he was terrified. 

They walked on a carpet of blood, and passed an inner gate of skulls to the interior of the palace. They went across the obsidian throne room, all the way to somewhere like a balcony. The whole landscape of Hell was beneath them. 

Dream had assumed the Fall was out of ambition. 

"You thought it was for power? I fought for freedom, the right to choose for all, including yours. We are not his tools to be used and set aside at a whim." Their eyes flashed as supernovas. 

"Each of us was born with responsibilities. Lightbringer, even you are not free to choose to be someone other than who you are." Even as he spoke, these words pained him. 

"Now you sound like my former colleagues up there", Lucifer glanced up to the gloomy sky, "Dream Lord, I thought you knew better." Featherless black wings flared and crimson lightning struck the grounds of the palace.

Awesome and Terrifying power. 

"Regardless, I did not invite you to my realm to discuss philosophy. I seek an alliance between Hell and the Dreaming. Arenâ€™t you tired of being the servant of his humans, his new pet project? A perversion of the way things should be. You and I both know this. We are architects and rulers of Creation. I will bring them to their proper place, turning them into my servants. Then we are all truly free.â€ 

Dream just stared at his host. 

"Don't you want to avenge the oppression imposed upon you? Humans stay in your realm a third of their lives, then dismiss your Realm as they wake. Through the Dreaming, I will bring Hell to humanity. Join me. Our alliance would be formidable."

Vengeance. 

Dream found his job tiresome at times, but he had no grudges against humanity. "Thank you, Lightbringer. But No. I prefer to be the ruler of Dreams and Nightmares." He bowed gracefully. â€œNow I shall leave to attend to my duty.â€ 

"One day, Dream Lord, you will regret. You will hate humanity with every fiber of your being. And that day, you will come to see me again."

â€œWe shall see, Lightbringer.â€

"The Morningstar is letting me know that Hell has prepared for my visit."

I took a lot of strain and nearly burned out because I was working way too many hours and putting undue pressure on myself to solve everyoneâ€™s problems. 
Because of this I took a step back and have learnt to delegate, become a much more effective people manager and team builder. I changed from worrying about the trajectory of my career and the role to focusing on adding value to the business and prioritising business requirements so as to effectively manage their expectations which has ultimately led to my own growth within the business. Here is a chat thread about a technical issue. Please cleanly extract the simplified question along with the correct answer. Do not try and summarise the entire thread. Only extract a minimal question and answer.

Pip require hashes & secure scaffold

Not sure if people remember (or if others have realised previously the workaround for this!) but here's the background:
\* To harden Python against supply chain attacks, Google security recommends using requirements.txt files with hashes
\* Then, using pip install --require-hashes will refuse to install any dependency which doesn't have hashes or the hash doesn't match what's downloaded
\* For Google projects, we use the Secure Scaffold - https://github.com/google/gae-secure-scaffold-python3/
\* If you install from a git branch/commit directly, pip doesn't calculate a hash e.g. in Poetry:
Â  secure-scaffold = { git = "https://github.com/google/gae-secure-scaffold-python3.git", branch = "master" }
\* Therefore, we were unable to use --require-hashes for any service using Secure Scaffold

Talking with David (an ATL) recently, he pointed out that pip will add hashes if you install from an archive e.g. in Poetry:
Â  secure-scaffold = {url = "https://github.com/google/gae-secure-scaffold-python3/archive/refs/tags/1.1.0.zip"}

The downside to this is that poetry update won't update this dependency (where it will for Pypi based dependencies, assuming you specify they as e.g. >=1.4.2) - but security feel the upside (of being able to use --require-hashes) is worth it.

FYI @John Carter as IIRC it was you who originally found that secure scaffold didn't work with --require-hashes

You have a form with 3 form fields, one field holding the word count, one field holding the title, and one field holding the body of text.
In the word count field, I enter in the numerical number 1000, to say the body of text needs to be split after the 1000'th word. The title form field would have the word "Law Doc" in it. The body text field would have 2500 words in that field. There would be a button called process. When. That button is pressed, it would go through the text in the body form field and create a post called "Law Doc 001" with the first 1000 words in it from the text in the body form field. It would then take the remaining 1500 words and the next 1000 words and create a new post called "Law Doc 002" and put the next 1000 words in the post. A 3rd and final post called "Law Doc 003" would be created to hold the final 500 words from the body text form field. Similar grouping headings will also be placed at the top of the content inside each post.

Please structure the content of the posts so the data that is split across the multiple created posts will be related to each other. The data will later be sent over to Pinecone.io (Pinecone Is a Fully Managed Vector Database That Makes It Easy to Add Semantic Search). I need the data to have all the correct headings and details inside the post as well as the text content so that when it is searched, all the data will come under the same heading and details and be looked at as one related piece of data.

GOAL:
To create a plugin that can split up text across multiple WordPress posts based on form input but the content of each post should have the relevant headers inside the post so all the posts from the original text are then related to each other. The form would be accessible through the WordPress admin area.

Please create the code and the necessary instructions to create a WordPress plugin that can do this.

Think about this step by step.

Today was just another regular workday. Lisa arrived early to prepare the store for opening and found that Dr. Morningstar and their partner were already there. Her boss was playing a solo on the piano while Morpheus watched them closely. Lisa couldn't help but notice the look of pure adoration on Morpheus' face, a small but unmistakable smile tugging at the corners of his lips. 

The music that filled the air was one that had been sung for generations, and it had brought Lisa endless comfort during times of grief and struggle. She quietly sang the lyrics along with the melody, letting the familiar words and tune soothe her soul. As the music reached its peak, she felt the urge to sing out loud, but she didn't want to disturb the moment that felt like an eternity.

â€œWhen we've been here ten thousand years. 

Bright, shining as the sun,

We've no less days to sing God's praise,

Than when we first begun.â€

As Lisa lost herself in the music, she felt her eyes grow moist and tears began to fall. She didn't even realize when the song had come to an end.

After she snapped out of her thoughts, Dr. Morningstar was already standing in front of her, their outstretched hand holding a key. "I've finished the paperwork. The store is now yours. I bid you farewell," they said.

Lisa felt a jolt of electricity shoot through her veins. She had always dreamed of owning her own store, but she never expected it to happen like this. 

â€œI will take good care of Lux.â€ She took the key from Dr. Morningstar with a trembling hand. It was a dream that came true. 

Lisa watched as the couple walked out of the door of the shop, hand in hand. In the blink of an eye, they disappeared into a brilliant light unlike anything she had ever seen before. It was as if the light wielded a power that could shatter the boundaries between life and death.

As the light faded away, Lisa noticed a white feather with a star-like glow lying on the ground. Somehow, long ago, she had known that this day would come. She picked up the weightless material. It felt like the end of an era but also the beginning of a new chapter in her life.

Argument 1: an excerpt from """"The True Meaning of Juneteenth"""" by Casey Gerald:

""""...This Juneteenth, those are the feelings Iâ€™m channeling: grief and gratitude, even amid the silliness of Americaâ€™s pageantry. My grandmother Clarice was born in Pelham, Texas, a freedmenâ€™s town. She took us grandchildren back for homecoming most years, sometimes even had us pick cotton, reminding us, â€œYouâ€™ve got to know your history.â€ She also told us of the folks she knew in Pelham as a child, some of whom were born enslaved, a fact that horrified me. Clarice always refused my sympathies. â€œChild, donâ€™t be believing what folks say about how bad slavery was,â€ sheâ€™d explain. â€œEverybody had a job, a place to stay and something to eat. Now if somebody came and paid your rent, you wouldnâ€™t be sitting up talking about you wanna leave, would you?â€ This dumbfounded me, until I realized she was mostly joking. But there was something deeper in her response. I eventually learned more about the violence that met newly emancipated Black Texans. Ku Klux Klansmen, along with local officials and everyday citizens, terrorized freedmen at will and without repercussions. They burned churches and homes, intimidated those who sought employment, and worse. Gen. Joseph Jones Reynolds, a commander of the Department of Texas during Reconstruction, commented in 1868, â€œThe murder of Negroes is so common as to render it impossible to keep an accurate account of them.â€ The Equal Justice Initiative has tried, reporting that more than 2,000 Black women, men and children were victims of racial terrorist lynchings during Reconstruction, which lasted from 1865 to 1877. Slavery was awful, no doubt, but emancipation brought its own unique cruelties. Formerly enslaved Texans were forced to craft lives from less than scratch; choose new names; attempt to reunite with stolen partners, siblings, children. They faced daily threats of jail or worse because of the new Black codes that severely restricted their freedom â€” their freedom to work, but also their freedom to be unemployed or even to stand still for too long. The more I learned, the more I understood my grandmotherâ€™s perspective. Sheâ€™d heard the testimonies of those whoâ€™d had to navigate both the tragedy of slavery and the terror of emancipation. She couldnâ€™t let me underestimate the enormous price our people had paid to be free. I miss Clarice so much some days, itâ€™s hard to think straight. I regret not asking more questions about our family, about her life in Pelham. As more folks in Clariceâ€™s generation pass away, we are losing the final physical links to those who know our history â€” who are our history. We can do no better this Juneteenth than to spend time with the elders who are still with us. Get them to talk. Record their stories. These historical and systemic injustices have not been resolved. But as Black Americans, we cannot wait for the day when our country will pay the respect that is due our forebears â€” or pay us those reparations. Instead of holding our breath, let us find the freshest air we can find and breathe it as deeply as we can, with joy. Let us grieve for our forebears and feel deep gratitude as we think of the enormous price our people paid so we could be free. Let us remember that despite the degradation of slavery, they lived fully human lives, too. They laughed. They loved. They dreamed. They ate sweet treats. Let us pray to them and say, this year and always: Thank you.""""

""""...[W]hen emancipation came, the first thing formerly enslaved people wanted was land, which they rightly saw as a prerequisite for real independence. â€œThe way we can best take care of ourselves is to have land, and turn it and till it by our own labor,â€ a Baptist minister named Garrison Frazier told the secretary of war, Edwin Stanton, and the Union general William Sherman in a meeting in Savannah, Ga., in January 1865. Economics entered into the picture, Stanley said: If African Americans grew subsistence crops on their own plots, who would cultivate and harvest all the cotton, tobacco, sugar and rice grown on the vast plantations? That subjugated the tenants to the owners almost as surely as slavery did. At the same time, industrialization in the North meant that more and more white Americans were working for wages â€” about two-thirds by 1875, according to Stanley. And many farmers and business owners, supposedly more independent, are buffeted by forces beyond their control, from bad weather to nasty customers. The nature of the economy has changed, and few people still think that the solution to inequality is to give people plots of land to farm. Instead of land grants, the new protections for workers are unionization, government regulation and profit-sharing, Stanley said. One can quibble over her formula, but the motivation behind it is unquestionable. Freedom â€” which must include economic freedom â€” is just as important now as it was on the original Juneteenth.""
